00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:34.510
So why is Loren Miller important?

00:06:34.510 --> 00:06:40.140
Why is a man who died
in 1967 relevant today?

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:44.720
Imagine yourself being sued by
your neighbors because you moved

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:48.890
into a neighborhood where
everyone looks different from you.

00:06:48.890 --> 00:06:55.590
Imagine the community using the
court system to force you to move.

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:58.610 position:56%
This situation might sound outdated,

00:06:58.610 --> 00:07:03.630
but discrimination is
not obsolete in 2016.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:08.540
Miller is relevant today
because he brought an end

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:11.750
to racial segregation in America.

00:07:11.750 --> 00:07:16.110
Because the struggle for civil
rights still continues today,

00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:20.550
because our ability to
promote progress cannot happen

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:23.760
without our court system,
our current freedoms,

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:28.380
or lack there of, are
rooted in the past.

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:34.570
Future changes depend on previous
court decisions and battles.

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:38.940
Loren Miller's story is a
story of an extraordinary man,

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:42.980
an unsigned hero who changed
the course of history.

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:48.500
A story that most people
today are unaware.

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:53.210
Federal Appeals Court Justice
A. Leon Higginbotham Jr.,

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:57.010
in paying tribute to the
black lawyers of our country,

00:07:57.010 --> 00:08:01.600
Higginbotham said in 1979, that
one man who would have been,

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:04.480
should have been on
the appellate court

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:10.610
or the U.S. Supreme Court
was a late Loren Miller.

00:08:10.610 --> 00:08:13.530
Others felt that he was
barely second in importance

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:15.540
to the late Thurgood Marshall.

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:23.860
Let me read briefly from
the opening of my book.

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:28.170
"Loren Miller died on Vasteel
Day, a fitting coincidence

00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:34.200
for a man dedicated to storming the
hush hush of court room injustice.

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:40.060
The coolness of the summer evening
of July the 14th, 1967, a Friday,

00:08:40.060 --> 00:08:42.890 position:56%
he succumbed to pulmonary emphysema.

00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:46.720
By noon on July the 19th, thousands

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:51.190
of people overflowed the
capacity of the Methodist Church.

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:53.690
Filling the pews or
crowding out doors,

00:08:53.690 --> 00:08:58.140
was virtually every back lawyer
and most of the judges in the city.

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:03.220
A multitude of greats, near
greats, among them dignitaries

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:08.830
and just plain Joes, came to pay
final respects to the great man.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:12.950
Lena Horne, the show stopping
beauty of film and song,

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:16.800
blacklisted in the 1950s
for her political views,

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:21.760
spoke at the ceremony and later
acknowledged hundreds of letters,

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:25.310
condolences, and telegrams.

00:09:25.310 --> 00:09:28.570
Mourners came from far and
near to attend the rites

00:09:28.570 --> 00:09:32.630
of the longtime civil rights
leader and prolific writer,

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:36.270
lawyer of intimidating
rectitude, and key strategist

00:09:36.270 --> 00:09:39.620
in the legal campaign to
overturn racial discrimination,

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:42.930
particularly in housing
and education.

00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:47.930
A man, who by sheer force
of will and determination,

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:55.050
improved the lives of those
on the periphery of justice."

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:56.350
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan:
Although Miller became one

00:09:56.350 --> 00:10:00.450
of the nation's most prominent and
influential civil rights attorneys

00:10:00.450 --> 00:10:06.920
of the 1940s to the 1960s, he grew
up in a mutable, unbearable poverty

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:10.090
on farms in Nebraska and Kansas.

00:10:10.090 --> 00:10:13.280
He wrote in his unpublished
autobiographical novel

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:18.400
of his childhood, that one night,
there was a sudden clapping

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:21.430
of the trap, and the
squeal of the rat.

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:26.190
Before the night ended, his
mother had caught 14 rats.

00:10:26.190 --> 00:10:32.530
They were what might be called
a family of itinerant squatters.

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:36.000
And here, I am going to return to
my book and read about the kind

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.700 position:56%
of world Loren Miller was born into.

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:45.300
"Loren Miller came into the
world on the western edge

00:10:45.300 --> 00:10:48.360
of the Omaha Indian
reservation in Pender,

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:52.450
Nebraska, on January 20, 1903.

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:57.790
He was born during the American
coal famine of 1902 to 1903,

00:10:57.790 --> 00:11:01.060
when fierce industrial warfare
erupted in the coalfields

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:06.700 position:56%
of Pennsylvania and caused a fuel
shortage with a broad ripple effect.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:11.210
In Nebraska, people turned from
burning coal to burning corn

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:14.180
to hear their homes and cookstoves.

00:11:14.180 --> 00:11:16.540 position:56%
In neighboring Council Bluffs, Iowa,

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:20.830
fuel-starved factories
threatened to shut down.

00:11:20.830 --> 00:11:25.840
Public schools in many states were
closed as coal supplies dwindled.

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:30.960
In Indianapolis, along the railroad
yards, poor people scavenged lumps

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:35.290
of coal and hauled them away
in wheelbarrows and sacks

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:39.150
in broad daylight in full
view of guards with rifles.

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:42.000
Eventually, the federal
government intervened,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.400
turning from the strikebreaker
to peacemaker

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:47.200
for the first time in US history.

00:11:52.130 --> 00:11:55.260
Perhaps, the atmosphere
of social, political

00:11:55.260 --> 00:12:00.100
and economical unrest surrounding
Miller's arrival presaged what lay

00:12:00.100 --> 00:12:03.730
ahead for him, a life on
the front line of justice

00:12:03.730 --> 00:12:06.800
where he would shine a
light into the dark shadows

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:08.970
of racism and inequality."

00:12:08.970 --> 00:12:19.010
Miller was soft spoken, slightly
built, intellectually brilliant,

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:22.460
extraordinarily sensitive,
and scholarly looking.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:27.150
The FBI reported he had
a small scar on his chin.

00:12:27.150 --> 00:12:31.470
Born in 1903 in Nebraska, he
was a son of a former slave

00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:33.910
who married a white woman.

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:37.310
He wrote that his mother's love
for his father was so great

00:12:37.310 --> 00:12:40.370
that it led her to
cross the color line.

00:12:40.370 --> 00:12:45.030
However, the hard scrambled
life, living in abject poverty,

00:12:45.030 --> 00:12:49.240
sometimes took a toll on his
mother, a former school teacher.

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:52.780
It was during these times that
she leaned heavily on her bible

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:55.370
to keep cheerful despite
the hardships.

00:12:55.370 --> 00:13:01.980
As a child, he was shy,
small, easily intimidated.

00:13:01.980 --> 00:13:06.800
He played ball just enough he
said, to keep from called a sissy.

00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:11.000
He grew up on a farm, but he didn't
like killing chickens or hunting.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.730
He cried at the sight of his
father bating a fishing hook

00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:18.510
with live sparrows
taken from their nest.

00:13:18.510 --> 00:13:22.510
Before Miller entered school, he
had taught himself how to read.

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:25.700
By the time he was
10, the townspeople,

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:27.760
who happened to be mostly white,

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:32.750 position:56%
began saying that 10 year old Miller
was the brightest child in school.

00:13:35.550 --> 00:13:39.520
When Miller was a boy living
in Nebraska, his father worked

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:41.810
at the courthouse as a janitor.

00:13:41.810 --> 00:13:44.710
His father would take him to
work where Miller would sit

00:13:44.710 --> 00:13:50.090
in the court room and listen to
the trials, watching and learning.

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:54.330
Whenever people asked him what he
was going to be when he grew up,

00:13:54.330 --> 00:13:56.490 position:56%
his answer always remained the same.

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:58.930
I'm going to be a lawyer.

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:06.510
This is what his father had
hoped him to be, and he did.

00:14:06.510 --> 00:14:10.340
Eventually, Miller's
family moved to Kansas.

00:14:10.340 --> 00:14:13.960
Displeased with his new
school, he wrote to complain

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:18.340
to his former school
teacher back in Nebraska.

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:22.150
In her reply, and this is 1914,

00:14:22.150 --> 00:14:27.450
she said don't you get discouraged
Loren about your school work.

00:14:27.450 --> 00:14:31.510 position:56%
If you do your best, you will surely
become far greater than the teacher

00:14:31.510 --> 00:14:34.740
who won't give you for
credit for what you do.

00:14:34.740 --> 00:14:38.650
Maybe you will be our
president someday.

00:14:38.650 --> 00:14:40.490
But if you do not become president,

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:45.410
you will surely feel some other
good place if you do your best.

00:14:45.410 --> 00:14:48.200
100 years ago, it was
impossible for a black boy

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:52.250
to even consider becoming
President of the United States.

00:14:52.250 --> 00:14:56.050
But this school teacher,
who happened to be white,

00:14:56.050 --> 00:15:00.150
believed that one day he would
do something very important.

00:15:00.150 --> 00:15:03.450
Determined to succeed, Miller
returned to his studies

00:15:03.450 --> 00:15:05.930
and worked harder than ever before.

00:15:05.930 --> 00:15:11.210
He went to college where he
studied to become a lawyer.

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:15.250
In 1928, he graduated
from Washburn College

00:15:15.250 --> 00:15:19.010
in Kansas, with a degree in Law.

00:15:19.010 --> 00:15:21.480 position:56%
Although Miller trained as a lawyer,

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:24.210
what he really wanted
to do was be a writer.

00:15:24.210 --> 00:15:26.450
To write novels and poems.

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:31.190 position:56%
But he was born at a time when
educated black people had 3 choices.

00:15:31.190 --> 00:15:37.250
In 1929, following the
death of his sister,

00:15:37.250 --> 00:15:40.700
Miller set out for Los
Angeles from Kansas.

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:42.840
He was a freshly minted
member of the BAR

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:48.340
who preferred political activism
and writing to the practice of law.

00:15:48.340 --> 00:15:51.660
Straddling a career as a lawyer
and journalist, when he arrived

00:15:51.660 --> 00:15:55.630
in Los Angeles, he quickly found
work as a newspaper reported

00:15:55.630 --> 00:15:59.240
for the largest black
newspaper at the time.

00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:02.850
Very quickly, he became the
newspaper's city editor.

00:16:02.850 --> 00:16:11.320
In 1932, using his clout at the
newspaper, he invited his friend

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:15.460
and prominent writer, Langston
Hughes, to Los Angeles.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:19.380
Shortly thereafter, they decided
to drive to New York and travel

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:23.010
to Russia to make a film
about blacks in America.

00:16:23.010 --> 00:16:27.130
That trip sealed their
friendship for the next 40 years.

00:16:27.130 --> 00:16:31.570
However, 5 months later, the
project ended for political reasons

00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:33.820
and Miller returned
to the United States

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:37.460
without the movie ever being made.

00:16:39.290 --> 00:16:44.180 position:56%
Soon after returning to Los Angeles,
Miller married Juanita Ellsworth,

00:16:44.180 --> 00:16:49.160
who in 1927, graduated from the
University of Southern California,

00:16:49.160 --> 00:16:53.200
where she studied to
become a social worker.

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:56.750
After his trip to Russia,
Miller, urged by his new wife,

00:16:56.750 --> 00:16:59.440
returned to the practice of law.

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:03.810
Although he sought to pursue the
writer's life, the need to put food

00:17:03.810 --> 00:17:07.510
on the table at the height of the
Great Depression propelled him

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:10.650
to work as both lawyer
and journalist.

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:15.010
He admitted that he was
dragged kicking and screaming

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:19.340
into the practice of law,
because you in those days he said,

00:17:19.340 --> 00:17:24.410 position:56%
a negro could be a doctor, lawyer or
school teacher and that's about all.

00:17:24.410 --> 00:17:28.840
He sacrificed his dream, not a man
given to brooding or self pity,

00:17:28.840 --> 00:17:32.380
Miller accepted the
career path he chose.

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:39.780
Miller and his wife Juanita
maintained a circle of friends

00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:44.340
which included, among others,
the singer and actor Lena Horne,

00:17:44.340 --> 00:17:47.730
Nobel Peace Prize recipient,
Ralph Bunche,

00:17:47.730 --> 00:17:52.650 position:56%
the Harlem Renaissance painter,
Aaron Douglas, and Carey McWilliams,

00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:56.360
editor of The Nation Magazine and
one of the Hollywood ten attorneys

00:17:56.360 --> 00:18:00.770
who defended black listed film
makers during McCarthyism.

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:06.420
As Miller's legal work focused
increasingly on civil rights,

00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:09.950
he became friends from with
prominent attorneys from the NAACP

00:18:09.950 --> 00:18:12.720
and The American Civil
Liberties Union.

00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:17.850
His reputation as a skilled
and brilliant attorney grew

00:18:17.850 --> 00:18:21.710
from local prominence
to national recognition.

00:18:21.710 --> 00:18:25.840
Miller became known locally in
Los Angeles as the go to guy,

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:29.170
if you were turned away
from an ice skating rink,

00:18:29.170 --> 00:18:31.310
a movie house or a restaurant.

00:18:31.310 --> 00:18:38.540 position:56%
He started taking on higher profile
cases that impacted national issues.

00:18:40.430 --> 00:18:45.690
During World War II, when President
Roosevelt authorized the interment

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:47.860
of Japanese Americans, Miller

00:18:47.860 --> 00:18:52.770
and his ACLU colleagues took
a very unpopular position.

00:18:52.770 --> 00:18:55.280
A position that not even
Jewish organizations

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:58.490
or the NAACP would take.

00:18:58.490 --> 00:19:01.780
Although Miller and his friends
fought hard to halt the curfew

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:06.800
and interment of west coast
Japanese, their efforts failed.

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:11.570
When the army trucks and soldiers
came for Miller's neighbors,

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:15.640
he did more than watch as they
were carted off to the camps.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:17.390
He had already arranged
the whole [inaudible]

00:19:17.390 --> 00:19:22.440
of his Japanese neighbors until
they returned after the war.

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:31.790
What is not so widely known, is
that in 1946, before Brown V Board

00:19:31.790 --> 00:19:34.900
of Education of Topeka
Kansas, Miller was part

00:19:34.900 --> 00:19:39.340
of an important class
action suit in California.

00:19:39.340 --> 00:19:41.230
It challenged the constitutionality

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:43.530
of segregating Mexican
American children

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:47.210
from California's public schools.

00:19:47.210 --> 00:19:50.040
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: On behalf
of the National Lawyer's Guild,

00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:55.200
the NAACP and the ACLU, Miller
submitted amicus briefs,

00:19:55.200 --> 00:20:00.210
friend of the court legal briefs,
in support of Mendez V Westminster.

00:20:00.210 --> 00:20:05.610
It was the first case to hold
as school segregation itself

00:20:05.610 --> 00:20:09.550
as unconstitutional and
violates the 14th amendment,

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:13.420
the constitution's
equal protection clause.

00:20:13.420 --> 00:20:16.970
What is important about the Mendez
case is that it was the first case

00:20:16.970 --> 00:20:19.850
to use sociological and
psychological evidence

00:20:19.850 --> 00:20:23.600
to show how segregation
damages children.

00:20:23.600 --> 00:20:26.600
And this was before Brown
V Board of Education.

00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:29.720
The uniqueness of Brown, is

00:20:29.720 --> 00:20:33.400
that it too used sociological
data as evidence.

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:37.150
That strategy led to the historic
decision to end racial segregation

00:20:37.150 --> 00:20:39.580
in America's public schools.

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:42.340
Although Loren Miller
did not stand up in court

00:20:42.340 --> 00:20:46.860
to argue the historically famous
Brown case, he drafted most

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:50.830
of the legal briefs that lead
to this monumental victory.

00:20:50.830 --> 00:21:00.120 position:56%
At the same time that Miller worked
on the Mendez case, Hattie McDaniel,

00:21:00.120 --> 00:21:03.690
the first black woman to
receive an Academy Award.

00:21:03.690 --> 00:21:07.230
She won an Oscar for her
role in Gone with the Wind.

00:21:07.230 --> 00:21:11.650
She was being sued because she had
audacity to buy and live in a house

00:21:11.650 --> 00:21:14.850
in Los Angeles's exclusive
Sugar Hill district.

00:21:14.850 --> 00:21:19.300
It was thought that there
was little possibility

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:23.110
that a black movie star
would be forced to move.

00:21:23.110 --> 00:21:25.730
However, this was a
time in Los Angeles,

00:21:25.730 --> 00:21:28.130
when the only way a
black person could live

00:21:28.130 --> 00:21:32.310
in a restrictive area,
was as a servant.

00:21:32.310 --> 00:21:35.690
It was a time when the black
residents of Los Angeles,

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:39.690
long fed up, filed more
suits contesting the validity

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:42.870
of restrictive covenants than
in any part of the country.

00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:49.210
On December the 5th, 1945,
Hattie and her 50 co-defendants

00:21:49.210 --> 00:21:50.950
and hundreds of sympathizers,

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:54.160
appeared in court in
all their finery.

00:21:54.160 --> 00:21:58.950
One writer said, that the stylist
atmosphere in the court was such as

00:21:58.950 --> 00:22:02.450
to make one wonder if the
judge would pour tea during the

00:22:02.450 --> 00:22:05.210
afternoon recess.

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:10.000
Ultimately, Miller won what
considered the first restrictive

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.830
housing case on constitutional
grounds.

00:22:13.830 --> 00:22:18.280
Afterwards, Miller wrote
a friend "I rushed home

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:21.970
to try the Sugar Hill case, and
succeeded in pulling a rabbit

00:22:21.970 --> 00:22:24.930
out of the hat by inducing
a local judge

00:22:24.930 --> 00:22:28.810
to hold race restrictive covenants
unenforceable on the grounds

00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:32.310
that such enforcement would
violate the 14th amendment."

00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:36.690
The Sugar Hill victory
was a monumental moment.

00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:41.470
For Miller, it was the first
of many high profile cases.

00:22:41.470 --> 00:22:45.710
Because Miller argued more
segregated housing cases

00:22:45.710 --> 00:22:50.930 position:56%
than any attorney did, 100, he
earned the title of Mr. Civil Rights

00:22:50.930 --> 00:22:53.110
of the Western United States.

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:59.800
By the mid 1940s, Miller
was part of a group

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:04.780
of brilliant NAACP legal
defense fund attorneys led

00:23:04.780 --> 00:23:09.570
by Thurgood Marshall, who
changed the course of history.

00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:14.510
Miller argued two landmark cases
before the US Supreme Court.

00:23:14.510 --> 00:23:18.650
In 1948, he argued the
famous Shelley V Kraemer case

00:23:18.650 --> 00:23:23.640
that all lawyers study
in law school today.

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:26.750
Alongside Thurgood Marshall
and Charles Hamilton Houston,

00:23:26.750 --> 00:23:30.370
Miller overturned racial
restrictive housing covenants.

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:33.690
This meant that it became
illegal to stop people from living

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:37.570
where they wanted because
of their race.

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:41.470
However, before the Shelley
case ever came to court,

00:23:41.470 --> 00:23:45.860
the NAACP held several meetings
across the country to determine

00:23:45.860 --> 00:23:48.100
which cases, which strategies,

00:23:48.100 --> 00:23:52.390
and which attorneys should stand
before the US Supreme Court.

00:23:52.390 --> 00:24:01.360
On the screen here, in this April
1947 letter from Loren Miller

00:24:01.360 --> 00:24:04.990
to Thurgood Marshall, found
here at the Library of Congress,

00:24:04.990 --> 00:24:09.490
Miller suggests that "They seek
outstanding lawyers from all

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:13.840 position:56%
over the nation to join forces" and
naturally he adds that he'll be glad

00:24:13.840 --> 00:24:17.610
to do whatever he can to assist.

00:24:17.610 --> 00:24:25.800
In this next NAACP letter,
dated October the 27th, 1947,

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:30.230
Thurgood Marshall confirms that
Loren Miller will argue one

00:24:30.230 --> 00:24:33.510
of the four cases before
the Supreme Court.

00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:36.670
According to Marshall, he
is under extreme pressure

00:24:36.670 --> 00:24:40.050
to select a big shot attorney,
not someone like Miller

00:24:40.050 --> 00:24:43.530
who had never tried
a Supreme Court case.

00:24:43.530 --> 00:24:45.980
In page 1, paragraph 3 here,

00:24:45.980 --> 00:24:48.820
Marshall mentions there has
been a lot of discussion

00:24:48.820 --> 00:24:51.580
on what lawyers will be selected.

00:24:51.580 --> 00:24:54.830
But here he says I am not
for having a person simply

00:24:54.830 --> 00:24:58.530
because he is refuted
to be a big shot.

00:24:58.530 --> 00:25:03.360
Then on the second page, Thurgood
says there is a tremendous amount

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:07.580
of fast foot work going on and
these cases are too important

00:25:07.580 --> 00:25:10.250
to tolerate any shenanigans.

00:25:10.250 --> 00:25:13.020
He stuck with Miller because
he had more experience

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:14.820
than any attorney did.

00:25:14.820 --> 00:25:21.040
[ Silence ]

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:24.110
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: Thurgood
Marshall remained unconvinced,

00:25:24.110 --> 00:25:27.280
in this particular case, that
the equal protection clause

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:31.270
of the 14th amendment
was the best strategy.

00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:34.770
Miller unflaggingly
persistent, convinced Marshall

00:25:34.770 --> 00:25:38.470
that the equal protection clause
and the due process clause

00:25:38.470 --> 00:25:41.380
of the 14th amendment
are intertwined.

00:25:41.380 --> 00:25:46.370
When the Shelley case finally
did reach the Supreme Court,

00:25:46.370 --> 00:25:49.630
it included nonlegal,
sociological materials

00:25:49.630 --> 00:25:51.670
on the affects of segregated
housing.

00:25:51.670 --> 00:25:58.740
Miller said "The question before
the Supreme Court was a simple one.

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:03.010
What the court decided was that
no state could enforce any law

00:26:03.010 --> 00:26:05.640
that deprives its citizens
of life, liberty,

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:09.350
or property without due
process and equal protection.

00:26:09.350 --> 00:26:12.190
In other words, restrictive
covenants violate the

00:26:12.190 --> 00:26:15.310
14th amendment."

00:26:15.310 --> 00:26:20.930
Thurgood Marshall said that the
Shelley case was unquestionably one

00:26:20.930 --> 00:26:26.110
of the most important in a
whole field of civil rights.

00:26:28.090 --> 00:26:32.830 position:56%
Aware that Miller's strength lays in
his command of the English language,

00:26:32.830 --> 00:26:35.180
Marshall again turned to Miller.

00:26:35.180 --> 00:26:37.570
This time to write the
majority of the brief

00:26:37.570 --> 00:26:39.620
in Brown V Board of Education.

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:42.390
Six briefs to be exact.

00:26:42.390 --> 00:26:44.730
Because of Miller's contribution,

00:26:44.730 --> 00:26:48.710
segregation in America's
public schools became illegal.

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:53.320
These cases laid the foundation
to end segregation in America

00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:56.440
and fueled the civil rights
movement and the passes of laws

00:26:56.440 --> 00:27:00.090
like the Civil Right Act of 1964.

00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:05.320
Yet, during the 50th and 60th
anniversary celebrations of Brown,

00:27:05.320 --> 00:27:07.740
Miller is not even mentioned.

00:27:07.740 --> 00:27:12.580
His erasure from our collective
memory is a real travesty.

00:27:15.990 --> 00:27:19.410
Loren Miller lived
a well rounded life.

00:27:19.410 --> 00:27:22.570
While he focused much of
his life on legal battles,

00:27:22.570 --> 00:27:26.290
he never fully abandoned his
love of writing and journalism.

00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:32.640
By the 1950s, Miller owned his own
newspaper, the California Eagle,

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:37.110
publishing the news for and about
the black residents of Los Angeles.

00:27:37.110 --> 00:27:40.460
Brad Pie, the sports
writer who worked

00:27:40.460 --> 00:27:44.290
for the California Eagle
Newspaper wrote how Cuz,

00:27:44.290 --> 00:27:46.050
as Miller was affectionately known

00:27:46.050 --> 00:27:49.630
around the newspaper,
enriched his life.

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:55.030
Using sports metaphors, Pie
wrote, in the civil rights field,

00:27:55.030 --> 00:27:58.250
to me he was a Jim Brown
of the legal profession,

00:27:58.250 --> 00:28:01.760
knocking down racial
barriers all around them.

00:28:01.760 --> 00:28:05.190
He dribbled through the courts
of the land like Elgin Baylor

00:28:05.190 --> 00:28:08.520
and scored as many
points in the legal field

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:11.900
as Wilt Chamberlain does
on the basketball court.

00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:15.730
As a lawyer, journalist,
author, publisher and scholar,

00:28:15.730 --> 00:28:20.980
he was an all around man as
Willie Mays is on the Diamond.

00:28:22.150 --> 00:28:28.710 position:56%
Towards the end of his legal
carrier, in 1964, he became a judge.

00:28:28.710 --> 00:28:30.550
Although Miller's intelligence,

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:33.690
admired by virtually
everyone he met,

00:28:33.690 --> 00:28:37.650
he had a tendency towards
razor sharp outspokenness.

00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:41.220
His asset whip was quick to burn
holes into the toughest skin

00:28:41.220 --> 00:28:44.820
and eat right through double
talk hypocrisy and posturing.

00:28:44.820 --> 00:28:48.980
I would like to conclude by
saying Miller was committed

00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:52.560
to making democracy
work for every American.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:58.950 position:56%
He said "It goes without saying that
I am opposed to any discrimination

00:28:58.950 --> 00:29:04.900
of any kind on racial and religious
grounds, or on any other grounds.

00:29:04.900 --> 00:29:08.520
I think that we must do that,
not only in simple justice

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:12.520
to minority groups of any
kind, but out on a realization

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:14.970
that the majority has
as big of stake,

00:29:14.970 --> 00:29:17.860
if not bigger, than the minorities.

00:29:17.860 --> 00:29:21.640
Either we shall have to make
democracy work for every American,

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:24.320
or in the last analysis,
we shall not be able

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:28.530
to preserve it for any American."

00:29:29.590 --> 00:29:34.600
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: Loren Miller
died in 1967 at the age of 64.

00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:38.250
His words ring out
just as loud today.

00:29:38.250 --> 00:29:41.690
His impact on all our lives
and freedoms is experienced

00:29:41.690 --> 00:29:45.720
when we can live where we
want, study where we want.

00:29:45.720 --> 00:29:47.540
His legacy laid the foundation

00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:52.210
for today's ongoing
progress for civil rights.

00:29:52.210 --> 00:29:56.670
In recognition of his many
contributions to the field of law,

00:29:56.670 --> 00:29:58.320
the state BAR of California

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:02.950
in 1970 established the Loren
Miller Legal Services Award,

00:30:02.950 --> 00:30:06.560
a lifetime achievement award
given annually to a lawyer

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:10.460
who has demonstrated
a long term commitment

00:30:10.460 --> 00:30:13.880
to providing legal
services to the poor.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:15.610
We owe much to this great man

00:30:15.610 --> 00:30:19.710
and we shall celebrate him
as a true American hero.

00:30:19.710 --> 00:30:22.510
Thank you, and now
for your questions.

