of burned some bridges because even
though he owned a newspaper and all

00:33:51.950 --> 00:33:56.350
of that, and he was involved in
so much especially in LA and all,

00:33:56.350 --> 00:34:03.240
but because he didn't promote
himself, he wasn't an opportunist

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:05.810
in that sense, I mean, he
ran for congress and lost,

00:34:05.810 --> 00:34:07.450
he didn't get past the primary.

00:34:07.450 --> 00:34:10.760
But only because people
were pushing him to do that.

00:34:10.760 --> 00:34:15.050
And there's a long letter
in his files about that,

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:19.740
about how he didn't exploit
himself for other people,

00:34:19.740 --> 00:34:21.410
you know to promote
himself in that way.

00:34:21.410 --> 00:34:24.410
Because basically he was
a [inaudible] kind of guy.

00:34:24.410 --> 00:34:29.190
His wife was more the society
maven, and she was involved

00:34:29.190 --> 00:34:32.660
in a great deal, women's
organizations,

00:34:32.660 --> 00:34:35.120
black women's organizations,
literary organizations

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:42.030
in California, and she and someone
else started an organization called

00:34:42.030 --> 00:34:45.840
the League of LA Arts in Los
Angeles when Langston Hughes

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:51.900
in 1939 could not find a theater
to put on one of his plays and out

00:34:51.900 --> 00:34:55.710
of that relationship they
started this literary organization

00:34:55.710 --> 00:34:57.010
which continues today.

00:34:57.010 --> 00:35:00.510
&gt;&gt; Let me ask another question.

00:35:00.510 --> 00:35:26.110
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:35:26.110 --> 00:35:28.510
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: I'm sorry,
I can't quite hear the question.

00:35:28.510 --> 00:36:05.040
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:36:05.040 --> 00:36:06.340
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: Well,

00:36:06.340 --> 00:36:09.280
he supported Pan-Africanism
I think intellectually,

00:36:09.280 --> 00:36:14.170
and also because in the 30's,
he was much more to the left.

00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:18.440
He mellowed out by the time
the 40.s and the 50's happened,

00:36:18.440 --> 00:36:23.080
because he belonged
to the John Reed Club

00:36:23.080 --> 00:36:26.540
and that's why he also had
an FBI file that started

00:36:26.540 --> 00:36:30.730
in I think in 1941 or 42.

00:36:30.730 --> 00:36:35.860 position:56%
So in fact his becoming a judge took
a long time because he was so close

00:36:35.860 --> 00:36:37.190
to the communists because he wrote

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:39.770
for a great many communist
publications.

00:36:39.770 --> 00:36:42.660
In the 60's, he supported
the Freedom Now movement,

00:36:42.660 --> 00:36:47.100
he wrote several articles
particularly in the nation,

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:49.540
and one is called Farewell
to Liberals,

00:36:49.540 --> 00:36:53.420
which is basically saying okay,
you've helped us white people,

00:36:53.420 --> 00:36:56.320
you've got us this
far, but now we need

00:36:56.320 --> 00:36:57.620
to lead this movement ourselves.

00:36:57.620 --> 00:37:00.290
So he was very clear there.

00:37:00.290 --> 00:37:04.740
Also in 1963, after
a shootout in 1962,

00:37:04.740 --> 00:37:09.740
he represented I think 14
black Muslims in Los Angeles.

00:37:09.740 --> 00:37:13.510
Actually, something very
similar is going on now,

00:37:13.510 --> 00:37:17.550
with the police force is that there
was a shoot out and one man died,

00:37:17.550 --> 00:37:21.640
I think 7 were shot and
injured, and there was case

00:37:21.640 --> 00:37:23.180
where 14 of them went to court.

00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:29.020
They lost but Miller was one
of the attorneys handling that.

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:34.180
So even though he sort of
distanced himself from the left

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:38.430
in a particular way, he
always was the Marxist

00:37:38.430 --> 00:37:44.920
and I think his distancing
himself from the communists later

00:37:44.920 --> 00:37:48.540
in the 50's and stuff was
just sort of self preservation

00:37:48.540 --> 00:37:52.990
because of what had happened
to other attorneys in that era.

00:37:52.990 --> 00:37:59.700
But this woman back here,
she wanted to ask something.

00:37:59.700 --> 00:38:04.430
&gt;&gt; Can you speak a little
more to his relationship

00:38:04.430 --> 00:38:06.000
with Charles Hamilton Houston?

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:07.550
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: He
was very critical of him,

00:38:07.550 --> 00:38:09.400
and there was a particular case,

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:14.320
I think it was called the
George Crawford murder trial,

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:16.790
and in 1935 or around there.

00:38:16.790 --> 00:38:19.260 position:56%
Even though he belonged to the local
branch of the NAACP in Los Angeles

00:38:19.260 --> 00:38:22.490
as one of the legal
team, he was critical.

00:38:22.490 --> 00:38:29.550
Nationally, during the time of the
Scottsboro Trial, he took the side

00:38:29.550 --> 00:38:33.470
of the communists against the NAACP
about how that was being handled

00:38:33.470 --> 00:38:37.220
and then because of that era,

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:40.180
Charles Hamilton Houston was
quite involved with the NAACP,

00:38:40.180 --> 00:38:42.500
so he was very critical
at that period

00:38:42.500 --> 00:38:47.570
but by the time the Shelley
case comes up in the mid 40's,

00:38:47.570 --> 00:38:51.230
he sort of changes his
tune to the point that,

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:54.500
I can't remember what was the
reason he wrote a letter to him,

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:58.880
but he compliments Houston on some
particular thing, so he had kind

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:02.580
of mellowed out, but he
was quite critical earlier

00:39:02.580 --> 00:39:06.460
in this one particular case that
had gone, he thought he had sold

00:39:06.460 --> 00:39:09.520
out this black man
in his murder trial.

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:10.820
Yes?

00:39:10.820 --> 00:39:12.480
&gt;&gt; Was he a published author?

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:15.240
Did he publish any books?

00:39:15.240 --> 00:39:19.470
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: Yes,
he has a definitive study,

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:27.220
it's called The Petitioners,
the History of the Negro

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:29.180
in the United States Supreme Court.

00:39:29.180 --> 00:39:34.510
And it came out about a
year before he died, 1966,

00:39:34.510 --> 00:39:39.990
and it started the definitive
history of the interaction

00:39:39.990 --> 00:39:42.740
between African Americans
and the Supreme Court.

00:39:42.740 --> 00:39:47.430
And it's quite interesting in
one respect, because in it,

00:39:47.430 --> 00:39:50.660
he doesn't mention his
involvement in several of the cases

00:39:50.660 --> 00:39:52.290
that he mentions in the book.

00:39:52.290 --> 00:39:56.960
He doesn't, he didn't
say oh I did this.

00:39:56.960 --> 00:40:00.090
No, it's very distanced
in that sense.

00:40:00.090 --> 00:40:06.840
And it's something that new lawyers

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:10.100
that are studying different
aspects of the law read.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:13.820
It's sort of a primary
text in that sense.

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:15.160
So it's a very interesting thing.

00:40:15.160 --> 00:40:19.690 position:56%
And that's where I also found out he
had this grand uncle who had a case

00:40:19.690 --> 00:40:24.470
that went to the Supreme Court,
I write about it in the book,

00:40:24.470 --> 00:40:27.360
who had a Supreme Court case,
a public accommodations case

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:30.890
that wound up in the
Supreme Court in 1883.

00:40:30.890 --> 00:40:34.940
And so this very cantankerous
grand uncle of his,

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:40.530
he went into a hotel restaurant,
sat down, and this was in Kansas,

00:40:40.530 --> 00:40:43.120
to be served and they
refused to serve him

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:44.820
and it even made the papers.

00:40:44.820 --> 00:40:51.290
And he marched immediately to
the Kansas US Attorney General

00:40:51.290 --> 00:40:57.180
and complained, and that case
would up going to the Supreme Court

00:40:57.180 --> 00:41:01.540
and was bundled I think
with 4 other cases,

00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:05.980
and what the Supreme Court
said, the decision was,

00:41:05.980 --> 00:41:07.680
it said that Congress had no right

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:10.990
to pass the Civil Rights
Act of 1875.

00:41:10.990 --> 00:41:12.530
So there was that.

00:41:12.530 --> 00:41:18.350
But the same man, his uncle, grand
uncle, he was in the civil war,

00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:20.470
along with two of his brothers.

00:41:20.470 --> 00:41:26.820
And he fought for his pension
for years, his veteran pension,

00:41:26.820 --> 00:41:28.950
for about 9 years or
something like that.

00:41:28.950 --> 00:41:33.690
And then he, I hope this isn't
offensive, and then he's quoted

00:41:33.690 --> 00:41:38.190
as saying, you know he
was fed up at that point,

00:41:38.190 --> 00:41:41.260
that he can't get his pension,
he loses in the Supreme Court

00:41:41.260 --> 00:41:43.140
and he says I'm going off
to live with the heathens

00:41:43.140 --> 00:41:44.940
and he moved to Oklahoma.

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:49.060
[ Laughter ]

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:50.380
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: But
it comes from this family

00:41:50.380 --> 00:41:56.100
that won't lay down,
they'll challenge it.

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:57.400
Yes ma'am?

00:41:57.400 --> 00:42:00.000
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much
for this presentation.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:01.300
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: Oh, thank you.

00:42:01.300 --> 00:42:03.000
&gt;&gt; I see Lester Grainger's
name here,

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:06.800
and I wanted to know the
nature of that relationship

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:11.960
and also whether Loren Miller was
a mason because Lester Grainger was

00:42:11.960 --> 00:42:14.640
and [inaudible] was,
Thurgood Marshall,

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:19.360
and there was a behind the
scenes cavalry of masons

00:42:19.360 --> 00:42:22.330
that supported the
Civil Rights Movement.

00:42:22.330 --> 00:42:24.720
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: I'm
not sure if he was a mason.

00:42:24.720 --> 00:42:26.480
I think he might have been.

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:33.690
I didn't find anything but then
you know, his files are massive.

00:42:33.690 --> 00:42:35.750
I do know spoke at
some Mason Hall's.

00:42:35.750 --> 00:42:37.050
Lester Grainger.

00:42:37.050 --> 00:42:41.250
He and Lester Grainger,
were political buddies,

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:44.450
they belonged to some of
the same organizations,

00:42:44.450 --> 00:42:47.170
political organizations,
leftist organizations,

00:42:47.170 --> 00:42:56.470
and when Loren Miller went to
become an editor of the New Masses

00:42:56.470 --> 00:43:01.590
and another newspaper in New York,
Lester Grainger and Miller were

00:43:01.590 --> 00:43:04.900
like roommates, and they kept
a really long friendship.

00:43:04.900 --> 00:43:07.280
And I think Lester Grainger
had come to California

00:43:07.280 --> 00:43:10.090
with the Urban League first,
before he became the head

00:43:10.090 --> 00:43:15.490
of the Urban League later on, and
so they were really good friends

00:43:15.490 --> 00:43:20.620
and I think Lester
also wrote columns

00:43:20.620 --> 00:43:27.520
when Miller bought the California
Eagle in 1951 that Grainger wrote.

00:43:27.520 --> 00:43:30.170
And every time Miller and his
wife would go to New York,

00:43:30.170 --> 00:43:34.620 position:56%
he would visit Lester Grainger and
his wife and family and all of that.

00:43:34.620 --> 00:43:37.140
So they were very, very close.

00:43:37.140 --> 00:43:41.540
In fact there was one letter
that Grainger writes him,

00:43:41.540 --> 00:43:45.260
wanting him to sort of endorse
something with the Urban League,

00:43:45.260 --> 00:43:49.300
and Miller writes back and
says you don't want to use me.

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:54.700
I still have that pink tinge
and you'll do more harm

00:43:54.700 --> 00:43:59.410
by having me write a letter of
endorsement or something like that.

00:43:59.410 --> 00:44:03.400
And it did follow him
for a long time.

00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:04.920
Any other questions?

00:44:04.920 --> 00:44:06.220
Yes, ma'am.

00:44:06.220 --> 00:44:08.410
&gt;&gt; Thank you Dr. Hassan.

00:44:08.410 --> 00:44:11.010
Just for clarification,
because Mendez

00:44:11.010 --> 00:44:15.130
versus Westminster
also is marginalized

00:44:16.590 --> 00:44:21.210
in history much like Miller.

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:30.360
So, within that case, is
Miller arguing for violation

00:44:30.360 --> 00:44:35.770
of the 14th amendment or is
he arguing that officially,

00:44:35.770 --> 00:44:39.390
Mexican Americans are
legally classified as white

00:44:39.390 --> 00:44:43.150
and therefore shouldn't
be subjected to separate?

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:46.050
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: I believe
it was just the 14th amendment.

00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:54.520 position:56%
And he was just an amicus brief, but
he happened to belong to the NAACP,

00:44:54.520 --> 00:44:57.870
he belonged to the National Argue

00:44:57.870 --> 00:45:01.100
and he was also a member
of the ACLU.

00:45:01.100 --> 00:45:06.130
And so, he wrote and
submitted briefs

00:45:06.130 --> 00:45:11.830
under those three organizations
but he didn't argue it.

00:45:11.830 --> 00:45:19.510
I was wrong at one point, I say
it in the book and I'm wrong,

00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:25.710
that he argued it because I
did come across a document

00:45:25.710 --> 00:45:30.560
that said he argued as an
amicus which is sort of rare,

00:45:30.560 --> 00:45:33.330 position:56%
but he didn't and I stand corrected.

00:45:33.330 --> 00:45:39.430
I don't think, and I haven't really
read the Mendez case carefully

00:45:39.430 --> 00:45:44.070
to see if they use the Treaty
of whatever, Hidalgo something

00:45:44.070 --> 00:45:49.580
or other, that for those that
don't know, in California,

00:45:49.580 --> 00:45:53.640
Mexicans traditionally have
been known as, are designated

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:57.270
as Caucasians, white, and even
though they're ill treated,

00:45:57.270 --> 00:45:59.860
it has something to
do with the history

00:45:59.860 --> 00:46:03.860 position:56%
of California being originally under
the ownership of Mexico and Spain,

00:46:03.860 --> 00:46:05.530
and the whole sort
of history of that.

00:46:05.530 --> 00:46:06.830
But I don't know.

00:46:06.830 --> 00:46:10.950
I haven't really read
it carefully to know,

00:46:10.950 --> 00:46:17.420
because when I research I'm just
looking for stuff for Miller.

00:46:17.420 --> 00:46:18.720
Yes ma'am?

00:46:18.720 --> 00:46:23.040
&gt;&gt; What is your next
project you're working on?

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:26.760
&gt;&gt; Dr. Amina Hassan: Well, I
am having trouble with that.

00:46:26.760 --> 00:46:31.440
I was going to do something
on Agustus Hawkins,

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:35.580
who's the first African American
and Congressman from the west.

00:46:35.580 --> 00:46:41.790
He was in the California
Assembly for 20 years

00:46:41.790 --> 00:46:46.120
and then he became a Congressman,
and he lived a long time,

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:49.240
and he was very important in
terms of labor and education.

00:46:49.240 --> 00:46:54.450
There's a Humphrey Hawkins Bill and
I went to UCLA where his papers are

00:46:54.450 --> 00:46:58.570
about a dozen times and
I just couldn't get fired

00:46:58.570 --> 00:47:02.530
up about him as a personality.

00:47:02.530 --> 00:47:04.360
What I liked about Miller is

00:47:04.360 --> 00:47:07.440
that he wasn't just
committed to black people.

00:47:07.440 --> 00:47:10.080
He was just about what's
right and what's legal.

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:15.050
And that's why he's associated with
Mexican Americans in California,

00:47:15.050 --> 00:47:21.800
with Japanese Americans, just very
close to Jewish American community

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:25.050
in California, particularly
southern California.

00:47:25.050 --> 00:47:28.280
And that's what made him
so interesting for me.

00:47:28.280 --> 00:47:31.630
And so I played around with the
Agustus Hawkins thing for a while.

00:47:31.630 --> 00:47:35.030
Now I'm thinking something
else, it just sort of popped

00:47:35.030 --> 00:47:36.420
up in my head the other day.

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:41.640
So I think I might ask someone else
to kind of give me their opinion

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:46.400
about it because when I
find that there are books

00:47:46.400 --> 00:47:51.300
that haven't been written like
Loren Miller, there wasn't any,

00:47:51.300 --> 00:47:53.720
and I thought more people knew

00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:56.730
about him even though I didn't
know very much about him.

00:47:56.730 --> 00:47:59.590
But as I've been speaking to
people, I found that really,

00:47:59.590 --> 00:48:03.420
I'm just surprised that he's in
because he really had done so much,

00:48:03.420 --> 00:48:05.350
there's an elementary
school in Los Angeles,

00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:07.390
there's a park named after him.

00:48:07.390 --> 00:48:15.090
He is the co-founder of the Los
Angeles Sentinel Newspaper in 1934.

00:48:15.090 --> 00:48:17.140
It is still functioning today.

00:48:17.140 --> 00:48:25.160
It has like over 150-175
thousand readers

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:28.180
and he doesn't even
get credit for that.

00:48:28.180 --> 00:48:31.910
It's his cousin, Leon
Washington gets the credit

00:48:31.910 --> 00:48:35.430
for being the founder of
this ongoing newspaper.

00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:40.170
He wrote editorials for it
all the way through the 40's.

00:48:40.170 --> 00:48:42.050
He was always the legal consultant

00:48:42.050 --> 00:48:45.420
and when his cousin Leon
Washington had a stroke,

00:48:45.420 --> 00:48:46.720
he took over this paper.

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:48.400
But he also helped found it.

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:53.240
In fact he brought his cousin
from Kansas to Los Angeles.

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:57.100
But he doesn't get credit for that.

00:48:57.100 --> 00:48:58.620
And that's really interesting.

00:48:58.620 --> 00:48:59.920
So yeah, there's another thing.

00:48:59.920 --> 00:49:02.420
I know California a little bit
better, even though I live here,

00:49:02.420 --> 00:49:03.720
and I live part of the
time in California.

00:49:03.720 --> 00:49:05.020
I know it a little better.

00:49:05.020 --> 00:49:06.320
But because, also I'm interested
in the west because there's

00:49:06.320 --> 00:49:07.620
so much written about African
Americans, it's mostly in the south

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:08.920
or the east coast, not too
much even from the Midwest.

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:10.490
But you are seeing more and more
things about African Americans

00:49:10.490 --> 00:49:12.230
and their contributions to the
history of the country in northern

00:49:12.230 --> 00:49:13.530
and mostly southern California.

00:49:13.530 --> 00:49:14.870
More books are coming out, and so
I kind of have more of an affinity

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:16.340
for that, and I always like
people who have been overlooked,

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:18.230 position:56%
or the kind of radio programs I
used to do, it's always about people

00:49:18.230 --> 00:49:19.530
who are disenfranchised
some kind of way.

00:49:19.530 --> 00:49:20.830
That always kind of
gets my juices going.

